undamental feature of a Jewish view of other religions. All religions must pass the test of whether they are compliant with a Jewish view of religions as being free from the worship of another God. With the advance in interfaith relations, positions have been affirmed that clear most major contemporary religions from the charge of idolatry. What remains of “idolatry” once it no longer serves as a tool for evaluating other faiths? Does the category continue to have theological appeal? What are its internal uses? A cadre of Jewish scholars and thought leaders explore in this volume what the continuing relevance of “idolatry” is and how it might continue to inform our religious horizons, allowing us to distinguish between good and bad religion, both within Judaism and beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGodxBiblical teaching. 0aGodsxBiblical teaching. 0aIdolatry. 0aJudaism |x Doctrines. 0aJudaismxDoctrines. 0aJudaismxRelationsxPaganism. 0aMonotheismxBiblical teaching. 0aPaganismxRelationsxJudaism. 0aReligious tolerancexJudaism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Jewish Studies.2bisacsh  aIdolatry, Judaism and world religions, Judaism and power, the self, nationalism, morality, image of God, Judaism and Christianity, kabbalah, magic.1 aAlon, Goshen-Gottstein, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEisen, Arnold, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFisch, Menachem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFishbane, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoshen-Gottstein, Alon, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHanoch, Ben-Pazi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarvey, Warren Zev, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/